h cancer: a prospective multicenter study. J Clin Oncol. 2011;29:3457-3465. 10.1200/JCO.2011.34.7625</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1200/JCO.2011.34.7625</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC3624700</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">21810685</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Rockwood K, Song X, MacKnight C, et al. &#xa0;A global clinical measure of fitness and frailty in elderly people. CMAJ. 2005;173:489-495. 10.1503/cmaj.050051</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1503/cmaj.050051</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC1188185</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">16129869</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Cataldo JK, Paul S, Cooper B, et al. &#xa0;Differences in the symptom experience of older versus younger oncology outpatients: a cross-sectional study. BMC Cancer. 2013;13:6. 10.1186/1471-2407-13-6</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1186/1471-2407-13-6</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC3576303</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">23281602</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42146765</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>18</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>18</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">1178-6930</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>19</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>OncoTargets and therapy</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Onco Targets Ther</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Research on Targeted Therapy for Malignant Tumors of the Biliary Tract.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>593457</StartPage><MedlinePgn>593457</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">593457</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.2147/OTT.S593457</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Biliary tract cancers (BTCs) are aggressive malignancies with rising incidence and dismal outcomes. This review synthesizes transformative advances in precision oncology and immunotherapy reshaping BTC management. Genomic profiling reveals targetable alterations-IDH1/2 mutations, FGFR2 fusions, HER2 aberrations, BRAF V600E-driving the clinical success of specific inhibitors (ivosidenib, FGFR inhibitors, HER2-targeted ADCs/antibodies, dabrafenib/trametinib). These agents demonstrate unprecedented response rates and survival benefits in molecularly defined subsets compared to chemotherapy. Emerging immunotherapies, including checkpoint blockade (especially for MSI-H/dMMR tumors), adoptive cell therapy, and cancer vaccines, show promise, often synergizing with targeted approaches. However, overcoming tumor heterogeneity, resistance mechanisms, and optimizing combination strategies remain critical challenges. This paradigm shift towards molecularly guided therapies offers significant hope for improving BTC patient survival.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2026 Yang et al.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yang</LastName><ForeName>Yuxin</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of General Surgery, Affiliated Hospital of Nantong University, Nantong, Jiangsu, 226001, People's Republic of China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhong</LastName><ForeName>Hutianyu</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of General Surgery, Affiliated Hospital of Nantong University, Nantong, Jiangsu, 226001, People's Republic of China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhang</LastName><ForeName>Jingjing</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of General Surgery, Affiliated Hospital of Nantong University, Nantong, J