ki. Approval was granted by the Ethics Committee of the Medical University of Vienna (Date 30.05.2023/No 1244/2016). GZ 2024&#x2009;&#x2212;&#x2009;0.901.338 of the Medical University of Vienna and Austrian Ministry for Science and Technology (subcutaneous mouse model), G23/036 of the Regierungspr&#xe4;sidium Freiburg im Breisgau (orthotopic mouse model). Informed consent was obtained from all individual participants or the parents included in the study. Consent for publication: Consent for publication was obtained from all individual participants or the parents included in the study. Competing interests: J.G. is consultant, advisory board participant and received honoraria for Novartis, Roche, Rhythm Pharmaceuticals, and Ipsen (not relevant to this study).</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2026</Year><Month>1</Month><Day>28</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>4</Month><Day>29</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>17</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>29</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>17</Day><Hour>6</Hour><Minute>29</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>16</Day><Hour>23</Hour><Minute>56</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42143334</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1186/s13046-026-03725-3</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">10.1186/s13046-026-03725-3</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42128849</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>13</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1348-4540</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>14</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Endocrine journal</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Endocr J</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Efficacy and safety of dabrafenib plus trametinib in BRAFV600E-mutated advanced thyroid carcinoma: Real world experience in 37 patients.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1507/endocrj.EJ25-0629</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study aimed to investigate the clinical efficacy and safety of dabrafenib plus trametinib for BRAFV600E-mutated advanced thyroid carcinoma in a Japanese real-world setting. We analyzed 37 BRAFV600E-mutated advanced thyroid carcinoma patients treated with dabrafenib plus trametinib between November 2023 and July 2025. Thirty-one patients (84%) had papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) histology, one (3%) had poorly differentiated thyroid carcinoma (PDTC) histology, and 5 (13%) had anaplastic thyroid carcinoma (ATC) histology. Among 31 PTC patients, dabrafenib plus trametinib was initiated as first-line treatment in 16 patients. The most common previous systemic therapy was lenvatinib (n = 16, 43%). The most common sites of target lesion were the lung (n = 23, 62%) and lymph node (n = 23, 62%). The median sum of the diameters of the target lesion was 40 mm (range, 8-166 mm). The objective response and disease control rates were 29% and 74% in patients with PTC, and 50% and 83% in patients with non-PTC (PDTC and ATC), respectively. The 12-month progression-free survival rates in patients with PTC and non-PTC (PDTC and ATC) were 73.2% (95% confidence interval [CI], 48.7-87.4%) and 60.0% (95% CI, 12.6-88.2%) (hazard ratio, 2.769; 95% CI, 0.691-11.1; p = 0.134), respectively. Dabrafenib plus trametinib treatment showed a response rate similar to that observed in clinical trials for BRAFV600E-mutated advanced thyroid carcinoma in this real-world study. However, long-term follow-up is required to determine the efficacy of dabrafenib plus trametinib treatment.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yamazaki</LastName><ForeName>Haruhiko</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-6640-3529</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Breast and Thyroid Surgery, Yokohama City University Medical Center, Kanagawa 232-0024, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Suganuma</LastName><ForeName>Nobuyasu</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Surgery, Yokohama City University School of Medicine, Kanagawa 236-0004, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kadoya</LastName><ForeName>Mei</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Endocrine Surgery, Kanagawa Cancer Center, Kanagawa 241-8515, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Masudo</LastName><ForeName>Katsuhiko</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Endocrine Surgery, Kanagawa Cancer Center, Kanagawa 241-8515, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Matsui</LastName><ForeName>Ai</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Breast and Thyroid Surgery, Yokohama City University Medical Center, Kanagawa 232-0024, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Saito</LastName><ForeName>Aya</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Surgery, Yokohama City University School of Medicine, Kanagawa 236-0004, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>14</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Japan</Country><MedlineTA>Endocr J<